--- Verification: read-only checks proving every scenario above landed
    correctly ---

21  postgres/21_checks.sql   -> identity db (switches to orders itself via \c)
    docker exec -i kotlincrud-postgres psql -U kotlincrud -d identity -v ON_ERROR_STOP=1 < postgres/21_checks.sql

22  mongo/22_checks.js   -> catalog db (reads notifications too via getSiblingDB)
    docker exec -i kotlincrud-mongodb mongosh -u kotlincrud -p kotlincrud --authenticationDatabase admin --quiet catalog < mongo/22_checks.js

--- Notes ---

- Every UUID/id used across these scripts is a fixed literal (not
  DB-generated), chosen so scripts in different files/databases can
  reference the same row without capturing generated values — e.g. Alice is
  always aaaaaaaa-aaaa-4aaa-8aaa-aaaaaaaaaaaa, her order is always
  20000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001.
- password_hash values are an obvious placeholder string, not real bcrypt
  hashes — hashing is application-layer and out of scope for a DB-only proof
  (see Archive/Development/Database §1.4).
- To start over from scratch: `docker compose down postgres mongodb && docker
  volume rm kotlin-microservice_postgres_data kotlin-microservice_mongo_data`,
  then `docker compose up -d postgres mongodb` and run from step 01 again.
